[30;1m625 | [0m[35mHere is an example for applying modifications to a writable mount and then committing those modifica[0m
[30;1m626 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m627 | [0m[35m 1. Mount it with a write overlay and add new files. The original archive is not modified.[0m

[30;1m313 | [0m[35mThis sidecar is stored at the TAR file's location or in `~/.ratarmount/`.[0m
[30;1m314 | [0m[35mRatarmount can load that index file in under a second if it exists and then offers FUSE mount integr[0m
[30;1m315 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m316 | [0m[35mHere is a more recent test for version 0.2.0 with the new default SQLite backend:[0m

[30;1m437 | [0m[35m## Union Mounting[0m
[30;1m438 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m427 | [0m[35m## Bind Mounting[0m
[30;1m428 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m429 | [0m[35mThe mount sources can be TARs and/or folders.  Because of that, ratarmount[0m
[30;1m430 | [0m[35mcan also be used to bind mount folders read-only to another path similar to[0m
[30;1m431 | [0m[35m`bindfs` and `mount --bind`. So, for:[0m
[30;1m432 | [0m[35m[0m
